== Common elements ==
[[Image:Ringmenu.png|thumb|left|The ''Mana'' series' Ring Command menu (from ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'')]]
A common element of the series is its seamless, real-time battle system. The system was developed by [[Koichi Ishii]] and improved upon by [[Hiromichi Tanaka]], out of a desire to create a system different than the one featured in the first few ''Final Fantasy'' titles.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cubed3.com/news/6783/| title=Square Enix on Nintendo DS, Wii, Online, Final Fantasy & More (Full Transcript)| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Riley, Adam| coauthors=Smith, Lesley| date=2007-02-08| publisher=[[Cubed<U+00B3>]]}}</ref> While action-based, the ''Mana'' battle system is intended to be playable even by newcomers as well as veterans.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.g-wie-gorilla.de/content/view/218/18/| title=Hiromichi Tanaka&nbsp;<U+2014> Final Fantasy III| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Nickel, Thomas | date=2006| publisher=G-Wie-Gorilla}}</ref> The system is coupled with the distinctive hierarchical "Ring Command" menu system, featured prominently in ''[[Secret of Mana]]'' and ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'', and to a lesser extent in later installments. Each ring is a set of icons with a textual infobox explanation which, upon selection, allow the player to use an item, cast a spell, look up in-game statistics, or change the game's settings. Navigation within a menu is achieved by rotating the ring through the cursor left or right, while switching to a different menu is achieved by pressing the up or down buttons.<ref name="SoM Manual">{{cite book| title=Secret of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=1993-10-03| publisher=[[Square Co.|Square Soft]]| id=SNS-K2-USA| pages=pp. 13<U+2013>14| chapter=Ring Commands}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Seiken Densetsu 3 Instruction Booklet| date=[[1995-09-30]]| publisher=[[Square Co.]]| language=Japanese| id=SHVC-A3DJ-JPN| pages=pp. 16<U+2013>17| chapter=Ring Command}}</ref> Although not part of the series, the spin-off ''[[Secret of Evermore]]'', developed by Square USA, was also built upon the "Ring Command" system.<ref>{{cite book| title=Secret of Evermore Instruction Booklet| date=1995-09-18| publisher=[[Square Co.|Square Soft]]| id=U/SNS-AEOE-USA| pages=pp. 10<U+2013>18| chapter=Ring Commands}}</ref>

The ''Mana'' series features several recurring characters and beings, including ''Final Fantasy'' creatures such as [[Chocobo]]s in ''[[Final Fantasy Adventure]]'' and ''[[Legend of Mana]]'',<ref name="1Up">{{cite web| url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3113932| title=Classics Column #1: Desperately Seeking Seiken| accessdate=2007-06-09| author=Parish, Jeremy| coauthors=Cifaldi, Frank, Gifford, Kevin| date=December 2003| work=[[1UP.com]]| publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Legend of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-06-07| platform=[[PlayStation]]| level=Monsters Encyclopedia| quote=Chocobo&nbsp;<U+2014> Nope, not the same Chocobo you know!}}</ref> as well as [[Common elements of Final Fantasy#Moogle|Moogle]]s in ''Secret of Mana'' and as a status ailment in ''Seiken Densetsu 3'' and ''[[Sword of Mana]]''.<ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Secret of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=1993-10-03| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]]| level=Great Forest| quote=Moogle: ...Puu... / Princess: Listen! He's laughing! / Sprite: No, crying. Pebblers have taken over their village.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Seiken Densetsu 3 Instruction Booklet| date=1995-09-30| publisher=[[Square Co.]]| language=Japanese| id=SHVC-A3DJ-JPN| pages=p. 22| chapter=Battle System}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Sword of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=2003-12-01| publisher=[[Nintendo]]| id=AGB-AVSE-USA| pages=p. 30| chapter=Battle}}</ref> Watts is a [[dwarf]] [[blacksmith]] wearing a horned helmet who upgrades the player's weaponry.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://psx.ign.com/articles/162/162141p1.html| title=Legend of Mana Review| accessdate=2007-06-14| author=IGN Staff| date=2000-06-06| work=[[IGN]]| publisher=[[News Corporation]]}}</ref> Usually, an [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[peddler]] is found outside of town areas and allows a player to [[saved game|save the game]] and buy supplies at high prices. This role is played by Neko the Cat in ''Secret of Mana'', and Niccolo the Rabbit in ''Legend of Mana'' and ''Sword of Mana''.<ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Secret of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=1993-10-03| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]]| level=Elinee's Castle| quote=Neko: Meow, I got caught, purr... need anything now? Meow busy travelers! I'll even save the game!}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Legend of Mana Owner's Manual| date=2003-12-01| publisher=[[Square Electronic Arts]]| id=SLUS-01013| pages=p. 4| chapter=Party Member Characters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nintendo.co.uk/NOE/en_GB/games/gba/sword_of_mana.html| title=Sword of Mana| accessdate=2008-02-14| author=Nintendo staff| date=2004-03-18| publisher=[[Nintendo]]}}</ref>

The Mana Tree and the Mana Sword, called [[Excalibur]] in ''[[Final Fantasy Adventure]]''{{'}}s English version, are recurring [[plot device]]s which have been featured in every game of the series. The mystical Mana Tree is a source of magic which sustains the balance and nature of the series' world.<ref name="DoM RPGamer" /> The Mana Sword is typically used to restore this balance when it becomes lost in the games.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamesarefun.com/gamesdb/review.php?reviewid=578| title=Review&nbsp;<U+2014> Children of Mana (Nintendo DS)| accessdate=2007-06-14| author=Fassino, Justin| date=2006-11-25| publisher=GamesAreFun.com}}</ref> ''Final Fantasy Adventure'' explains that if the Mana Tree dies, a member of the Mana Family will become the "seed" of a new Tree. A sprout of the Mana Tree is called a Gemma, while protectors of the Tree, who wield the Mana Sword, are called Gemma Knights.<ref name="FFATree">{{cite video game| title=[[Final Fantasy Adventure]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=1991-11-01| platform=[[Game Boy]]| level=Mana Tree| quote=Mother: Now that the Mana Tree is lost. We need.. a new gemma of the Mana Tree. / Heroine: .. New tree? / Mother: Remember what I told you? We are the seeds of the Mana Tree. We will be a bud called gemma and we become a tree. And the Gemma Knights fight to guard it. I became the Gemma last time we lost the Tree. / Heroine: That tree..? Was it you..? / Mother: ..Yes, Heroine. But.. you are the last member of us Mana Family. To preserve the Mana Tree we need you to stay here and become the gemma. But.. Heroine.. Nobody else can decide for your life but you.. / Heroine: I will, Mom. I will be the new Tree of Mana. [<U+2026>]}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Final Fantasy Adventure]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=1991-11-01| platform=[[Game Boy]]| level=Dime Tower| quote=Tablet: Gemma Knight with the rusty sword will be tested. The true Gemma Knight should be given the legendary sword, Excalibur....! King of Vandole got the mighty power of Mana. The only one who can stand against is the .... Gemma Knight.... with the.... Excalibur....}}</ref> In ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'', a Goddess is said to have turned into the Mana Tree after creating the world with the Mana Sword.<ref name="God Beasts">{{cite video game| title=[[Seiken Densetsu 3]] (Neill Corlett's fan translation)| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-08-27| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]]| version=1.01| level=Introduction | quote=Once, when the world was yet trapped in darkness, the goddess of Mana felled 8 incarnations of disaster that guided the world to destruction, the God-Beasts, with the Sword of Mana, and sealed them in 8 stones. And, as the darkness left, the world was created. The goddess of Mana turned herself into a tree, and fell asleep. Many years passed... [<U+2026>]}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Seiken Densetsu 3]] (Neill Corlett's fan translation)| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-08-27| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]]| version=1.01| level=Temple of Light| quote=Priest of Light: It is the implement which the goddess used to create the world. He who holds the sword of mana has the power to reshape the world, create and destroy life... it sleeps at the base of the mana tree under constant guard by the faerie.}}</ref> The Mana Tree is destroyed near the game ending in ''Final Fantasy Adventure'' and ''[[Secret of Mana]]'', but a character becomes the new Mana Tree in the former game.<ref name="FFATree" /><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Secret of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=1993-10-03| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] | level=Pure Land| quote=Hero: Where are we? There's no Mana Tree... / Sprite: What the... After all we've been through! It's THANATOS'S doing!}}</ref>

[[Image:SD3 Elemental Spirits.jpg|thumb|The Faerie of ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'' surrounded by spirits of the eight types]]
Elemental Spirits, also called Mana Spirits, are beings who govern the [[elemental|magic elements]] of the series' world, and are at the core of the games' [[magic (gaming)|magic system]] as they are used to cast [[Magic (gaming)|magic spells]].<ref name="DoM RPGamer">{{cite web| url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/sd/seiken4/seiken4prev.html| title=A New Era Dawns for Mana| accessdate=2007-06-14| author=Athab, Majed| date=2007-04-15| publisher=[[RPGamer]]}}</ref> Eight types of spirits have appeared in the series since ''[[Secret of Mana]]'', and each embodies a different element. Their names are [[homonym]]s of mythological beings or [[phenomenon|phenomena]].<ref name="SoM Spirits">{{cite book| title=Secret of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=1993-10-03| publisher=[[Square Co.|Square Soft]]| id=SNS-K2-USA| pages=pp. 36<U+2013>39| chapter=Sprite Magic / The Girl's Magic}}</ref> In ''Secret of Mana'' and ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'', usage of their power is enabled upon the main characters' meeting with them.<ref name="SoM Spirits">{{cite book| title=Secret of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=1993-10-03| publisher=[[Square Co.|Square Soft]]| id=SNS-K2-USA| pages=pp. 36<U+2013>39| chapter=Sprite Magic / The Girl's Magic}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Seiken Densetsu 3 Instruction Booklet| date=1995-09-30| publisher=[[Square Co.]]| language=Japanese| id=SHVC-A3DJ-JPN| pages=p. 25| chapter=Growth System}}</ref> In ''[[Legend of Mana]]'', the spirits serve as factors in the [[Legend of Mana#Elemental spirits|Land Creation System]].<ref name="LoM Spirits">{{cite book| title=Legend of Mana Owner's Manual | date=[[2003-12-01]] | publisher=[[Square Electronic Arts]]| id=SLUS-01013| pages=p. 9 | chapter=Land Creation System}}</ref> In ''Legend of Mana'' and ''Sword of Mana'', multiple spirits of the same elemental type appear.<ref name="LoM Spirits" /><ref>{{cite book| title=Sword of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=2003-12-01| publisher=[[Nintendo]]| id=AGB-AVSE-USA | pages=p. 26| chapter=Battle}}</ref> In terms of storyline, in ''Seiken Densetsu 3'', the spirits are charged to protect the Mana Stones in which the Mana Goddess sealed eight elemental God Beasts.<ref name="God Beasts" /><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Seiken Densetsu 3]] (Neill Corlett's fan translation)| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-08-27| platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]]| version=1.01| level=Temple of Light| quote=Faerie: the eight spirits who guarded the mana stones... they could probably help us.  With their combined energy, we may even be able to open the gate...}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Legend of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-06-07| platform=[[PlayStation]]| level=World History Encyclopedia | quote=The Creation&nbsp;<U+2014> The Moon Gods created land and ocean, trees and flowers, and gave them light and the power to determine their fate. The light became the Elemental Spirits, riding in the sky. They released bountiful light, and were full of desire to serve the Moon Gods' will. The Moon Gods then finally returned to slumber.}}</ref> In ''[[Dawn of Mana]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s North American version, each spirit speaks with a particular European accent, such as French or Scottish.<ref name="accent">{{cite web| url=http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/dawnofmana/index.html| title=RPGFan Reviews&nbsp;<U+2014> Dawn of Mana| accessdate=2007-06-16| author=Rubinshteyn, Dennis| date=2007-05-18| work=[[RPGFan]]| publisher=Cerberus Media Group}}</ref>

[[Image:Rabite Mana.png|left|thumb|A typical Rabite from ''[[Children of Mana]]'']]

Rabites, known as {{nihongo|Rabi|<U+30E9><U+30D3>}} in the Japanese versions of the games, are [[fictional character|fictional]], [[rabbit]]-like creatures appearing as a common enemy in the series since its beginning. The Rabite has become a sort of mascot for the ''Mana'' series, much the same way as the [[Chocobo]] represents ''[[Final Fantasy]]'', and is one of its most recognizable icons.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3153961| title=Preview: Dawn of Mana| accessdate=2007-06-12| author=Parish, Jeremy| date=2006-09-22| work=[[1UP.com]]| publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]}}</ref> The Rabite resembles a bodiless, one-toothed rabbit with large ears that curve upward and form a point at the tip, and a round, puffy pink tail that moves by hopping along the ground. It is most commonly yellow colored, but also pink, lilac, black, and white, and are variously minor enemies, "superboss" characters and even friendly units and pets.<ref>{{cite book| title=Le Guide Officiel Nintendo "Secret of Mana"| date=1994-11-24| publisher=[[Nintendo]]| id=SNSP-K2-FRA/SFRA| pages=p. 64| chapter=La gallerie des monstres| language=French}}</ref><ref name="SD3guide">{{cite book| title={{nihongo|Seiken Densetsu 3 Kisochishikihen|<U+8056><U+5263><U+4F1D><U+8AAC>3 <U+57FA><U+790E><U+77E5><U+8B58><U+7DE8>|Seiken Densetsu 3 Basic Knowledge Volume}}| date=1995-10-13| publisher=[[NTT Publishing]]| isbn=4-87188-805-3| pages=p. 131| chapter=Monster Picture Book| language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name="SD3guide" /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cubed3.com/review/321/2/ | title=Seiken Densetsu 3 / Secret of Mana 2 Review| accessdate=2007-06-13| author=Riley, Adam| date=2006-03-10| publisher=[[Cubed<U+00B3>]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://guidesarchive.ign.com/guides/12141/features.html| title=Legend of Mana Strategy Guide| accessdate=2007-06-18| author=Kepper, Sean| date=2000-06-21| work=[[GameSpot]]| publisher=[[CNET Networks]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/mobile/seiken/fom/| title=<U+8056><U+5263><U+4F1D><U+8AAC> Friends of Mana| accessdate=2007-06-13| publisher=[[Square Enix]]| language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://ds.gamespy.com/nintendo-ds/seiken-densetsu-heroes-of-mana/779564p1.html| title=Heroes of Mana Preview| accessdate=2007-06-13| author=Leeper, Justin| date=2007-04-10| work=[[GameSpy]]| publisher=[[News Corporation]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gaming-age.com/cgi-bin/reviews/review.pl?sys=ps2&game=dawnofmana| title=Dawn of Mana Review for PlayStation 2| accessdate=2007-06-13| author=Laramie, Chris| publisher=Gaming Age}}</ref> Rabites are also mentioned in ''[[Final Fantasy X-2]]'' with an accessory comically named "Rabite's Foot", which increases a character's [[luck]] statistic.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gamespot.com/features/6087217/p-94.html| title=Final Fantasy X-2 Game Guide| accessdate=2007-06-13| author=Kolar, Damir| date=[[2004-02-02]]| work=[[GameSpot]]| publisher=[[CNET Networks]]| pages=p. 94}}</ref> Rabites have appeared prevalently in several pieces of ''Mana'' merchandise, including plush dolls, cushions, lighters, mousepads, straps, telephone cards, and T-shirts.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rpgfan.com/pics/seiken4/products.html| title=Legend of Mana Products| accessdate=2007-06-13| work=[[RPGFan]]| publisher=Cerberus Media Group}}</ref>

[[Image:Flammie.jpg|thumb|Characters riding atop Flammie (from ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'')]]
Flammie, sometimes spelled Flammy, is the name of a fictional species of flying dragons, as well as the proper name of some its members, featured in several games of the series. A Flammie's appearance is a mixture of [[dragon|draconian]], [[mammal]]ian, and [[reptile|reptilian]] features, and its coloring has varied throughout the series. Flammies typically serve as a mean of transportation in the game by allowing a player's characters to ride on a Flammie's back to different locations in the game's world. In ''[[Secret of Mana]]'' and ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'', the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Nintendo]]'s [[Mode 7]] graphic capabilities allows the player to control a Flammie from either a "behind the back" [[Grammatical person|third-person]] or top-down perspective, and fly over the landscape as it scrolls beneath them.<ref>{{cite book| title=Secret of Mana Instruction Booklet| date=1993-10-03| publisher=[[Square Co.|Square Soft]]| id=SNS-K2-USA| pages=pp. 30<U+2013>31 | chapter=Modes of Travel}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=Seiken Densetsu 3 Instruction Booklet| date=1995-09-30| publisher=[[Square Co.]]| language=Japanese| id=SHVC-A3DJ-JPN | pages=p. 27| chapter=Means of Local Transportation}}</ref> In ''[[Children of Mana]]'', the player selects on a world map a number of destinations he or she wishes to fly to with a Flammie.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/mana/| title=The World of Mana| accessdate=2007-06-12| publisher=[[Square Enix]]| language=Japanese}}</ref> In terms of story, the Flammies were created by the Moon Gods, and are part of an endless cycle of destruction and rebirth as the stronger versions of Flammies<U+2014>known as Mana Beasts, or {{nihongo|God Beasts|<U+795E><U+7363>|Kami Kemono}} in Japanese<U+2014>destroy the world and the Mana Sword and Tree restore the world.<ref>{{cite video game| title=[[Legend of Mana]]| developer=[[Square Co.]]| date=2000-06-07| platform=[[PlayStation]]| level=World History Encyclopedia| quote=Dark Clouds - [<U+2026>] But dark clouds came to Fa'Diel, and the Moon Gods created greater beasts, and set them loose upon the land. The Flammies often quarreled, and the cycle of creation and destruction repeated endlessly. / Rebirth - [<U+2026>] Each Moon God chose a Flammy and gave it a stone. The Flammies rode into the sky. They were born of the earth to ride in the sky and return to the earth. They became a flying river of Mana. / The Revelation&nbsp;<U+2014> The Flammies turned their backs on the Moon Gods and flew into the air. The Moon Gods turned into stars, and the Flammies never came back down. [<U+2026>]}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game | title=[[Secret of Mana]] | developer=[[Square Co.]] | date=1993-10-03 | platform=[[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] | level=Mana Fortress | quote=Sprite: It's a Mana Beast! / Princess: Isn't it a Flammie? / Hero: I guess Flammies were once Mana Beasts...}}</ref><ref>{{cite video game | title=[[Legend of Mana]] | developer=[[Square Co.]] | date=2000-06-07 | platform=[[PlayStation]] | level=World History Encyclopedia | quote=Flammies&nbsp;<U+2014> Then, a beautiful yet powerful beast appeared, awakening the Moon Gods. The Moon Gods named this beast of strength and beauty Flammy. Whenever one of the Moon Gods would fall asleep, another Flammy would appear. Eventually, Flammies of all six colors came to populate all the land.}}</ref>

==Music==
The ''Mana'' series has had several different [[composer]]s. ''[[Final Fantasy Adventure]]'' was composed by [[Kenji Ito]]; it was his second original score.<ref name="Ito website">{{cite web| url=http://ito.cocoebiz.com/news/index.php| title=News| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=CocoeBiz staff| work=Kenji Ito's Official English Website| publisher=CocoeBiz}}</ref> Ito's music is mainly inspired by images from the game rather than outside influences.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ito.cocoebiz.com/interviews/interview1.php| title=Interview with CocoeBiz in December 2004| accessdate=2007-06-15| date= December 2004| author=Ezaki, Kahori| coauthors=McCawley, James| work=Kenji Ito's Official English Website| publisher=CocoeBiz}}</ref> The scores for ''[[Secret of Mana]]'' and ''[[Seiken Densetsu 3]]'' were both composed by [[Hiroki Kikuta]]. Despite difficulties in dealing with the hardware limitations, Kikuta tried to express, in the music of ''Secret of Mana'', two "contrasting styles", namely himself and the game. This was to create an original score which would be neither [[pop music]] nor standard [[video game music|game music]].<ref>{{cite book| author=Kikuta, Hiroki| title=''Seiken Densetsu 2 Original Sound Version'' (liner notes)| date=1995-08-25 |publisher=[[NTT Publishing]]| language=Japanese| id=PSCN-5030}}</ref> Kikuta worked on the music for the two  games mostly by himself, spending nearly 24&nbsp;hours a day in his office, alternating between composing and editing to create an immersive three-dimensional sound.<ref name= "mana">{{cite web| url=http://www.square-haven.net/news/?id=1176| title=Where Angels Fear to Tread: A Conversation with Hiroki Kikuta| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Jeriaska| coauthors=Yamamoto, Taka| date=2007-06-09| work=Square Haven}}</ref> Kikuta considers the score for ''Secret of Mana'' his favorite creation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rocketbaby.net/interviews_hiroki_kikuta_1.html| title=Interview with Hiroki Kikuta| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=RocketBaby staff| date=2001| work=RocketBaby| publisher=Hollow Light Media}}</ref> His compositions for ''Secret of Mana'' and ''Seiken Densetsu 3'' were partly inspired by natural landscapes.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.spelmusik.net/intervjuer/hiroki_kikuta_eng.html| title=Interview with Hiroki Kikuta| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Kalabakov, Daniel| date=2003-01-06| work=Spelmusik.net}}</ref> In 1995, Kikuta released an experimental album of [[arrangement|arranged music]] from the two installments, titled ''Secret of Mana +'', which features one 50-minute long track.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rpgfan.com/soundtracks/som+/index.html | title=RPGFan Soundtracks&nbsp;<U+2014> Secret of Mana+| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Kalabakov, Daniel| date=2002-05-19| work=[[RPGFan]]| publisher=Cerberus Media Group}}</ref>

''[[Legend of Mana]]'''s score was composed by [[Yoko Shimomura]], and of all her compositions, she considers it the one that best expresses herself.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rocketbaby.net/interviews_yoko_shimomura.shtml| title=RocketBaby's Interview with Yoko Shimomura| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=RocketBaby staff| date=2002| work=RocketBaby| publisher=Hollow Light Media}}</ref> Kenji Ito returned to the series with ''[[Sword of Mana]]''. He also composed roughly one third of the ''[[Children of Mana]]'' soundtrack, while the rest was composed by [[Masaharu Iwata]] and Takayuki Aihara. Ito was the main composer for ''[[Dawn of Mana]]'', assisted by [[Tsuyoshi Sekito]], Masayoshi Soken, and [[Junya Nakano]], as well as main theme composer [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]].<ref name="Ito website" /> In North America, purchasers of ''Dawn of Mana'' from participating retailers were offered a sampler disc, titled ''Breath of Mana'', which features a selection of tracks from the game.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q1-2007/032607a.html| title=The Breath of Dawn on a New Hero of Mana| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Blair, Jody| date=2007-03-26| publisher=[[RPGamer]]}}</ref> Yoko Shimomura returned to the series with ''[[Heroes of Mana]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rpgamer.com/news/Q3-2006/091306a.html| title=Square Enix Unveils Final Fantasy XII Sequel, Three More Games| accessdate=2007-06-15| author=Boulette, Bryan| date=2006-09-13| publisher=[[RPGamer]]}}</ref>

==Printed adaptations==
A 5-volume [[manga]] based on ''[[Legend of Mana]]'' was drawn by [[Shiro Amano]] and published in Japan by [[Enterbrain]] between 2000 and 2002.<ref name="legendmanga">{{cite web| url=http://www.enterbrain.co.jp/cgi-bin/psearch/psearch.cgi?proc=search&word=writer&text=%C5%B7%CC%EE%A5%B7%A5%ED| title=Search results for Shiro Amano| accessdate=2007-06-09| publisher=[[Enterbrain]]| language=Japanese}}</ref> It features a comedic story about the game's main character, here named Toto. A [[German language|German]] version was published by Egmont Manga & Anime in 2003.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ehapa.de/ehapa/content/e22/e49/e688/e699/newsletter_22_2003.pdf| title=Egmont Ehapa&nbsp;<U+2014> Newsletter Nr. 22 vom 18.03.2003 | accessdate=2007-06-10| date=2003-03-18| format=PDF| publisher=[http://www.ehapa.de/ Egmont Ehapa]| pages=p. 3| language=German}}</ref> A collection of 4-panel comic strips, drawn by various authors and titled ''Sword of Mana Yonkoma Manga Theatre'', was published in Japan by Square Enix on [[16 January]] [[2004]]. It included a [[questionnaire]] that, if sent back, allowed participants to win illustrations signed by [[Koichi Ishii]] and [[Shinichi Kameoka]], as well as special [[T-shirt]]s.<ref name="gamebooks">{{cite web| url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/gamebooks/seiken/index.html| title=<U+65B0><U+7D04> <U+8056><U+5263><U+4F1D><U+8AAC>| accessdate=2007-06-11| publisher=[[Square Enix]]| language=Japanese}}</ref> Enterbrain also published a ''[[Sword of Mana]]'' manga adaptation in Japan on [[25 February]] [[2004]], drawn by a collaboration of authors led by Shiro Amano.<ref name="swordmanga">{{cite web| url=http://www.enterbrain.co.jp/jp/p_catalog/book/2004/4-7577-1753-9.html| title=Shinyaku Seiken Densetsu Anthology Comic| accessdate=2007-06-09| publisher=[[Enterbrain]]| language=Japanese}}</ref> Two days later, Square Enix published a 2-volume [[novelization]] of ''Sword of Mana'' in Japan written by Matsui Oohama.<ref name="gamebooks" /> An original manga, named ''Seiken Densetsu: Princess of Mana'', was drawn by Satsuki Yoshino and published in the Japanese magazine ''[[Gangan Comics#Gangan Powered|Gangan Powered]]'' on [[22 February]] [[2007]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/powered/comics/| title=<U+30AC><U+30F3><U+30AC><U+30F3><U+30D1><U+30EF><U+30FC><U+30C9><U+65B0><U+767B><U+5834><U+FF01><U+FF01>| accessdate=2007-06-10| publisher=[[Square Enix]]| language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.square-enix.co.jp/magazine/lineup-book.html| title=Square Enix - <U+88FD><U+54C1><U+30E9><U+30A4><U+30F3><U+30CA><U+30C3><U+30D7>| accessdate=2007-06-10| publisher=[[Square Enix]]| language=Japanese}}</ref>
{{-}}

